WEBVTT

00:00:08.404 --> 00:00:12.908 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎The seahorse 
‎has a very unusual feature for a fish:

00:00:12.908 --> 00:00:15.286 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎a prehensile, or grasping, tail.

00:00:15.286 --> 00:00:18.956 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎This tail can anchor 
‎the seahorse to one spot,

00:00:18.956 --> 00:00:21.667 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎resisting the ocean currents
‎that surround it. 

00:00:23.335 --> 00:00:25.671 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎How does it work?

00:00:25.671 --> 00:00:30.092 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎The cross-section 
‎of the seahorse’s tail is square,

00:00:30.092 --> 00:00:33.637 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎not round like that 
‎of most other animals with gripping tails.

00:00:33.637 --> 00:00:35.764 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎In contrast with a round shape,

00:00:35.764 --> 00:00:38.809 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎this square shape 
‎allows the tail to contact a greater area

00:00:38.809 --> 00:00:40.811 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎of the surface being gripped,

00:00:40.811 --> 00:00:43.314 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎making it more difficult to dislodge.

00:00:43.314 --> 00:00:45.316 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎It can also

00:00:45.316 --> 00:00:48.485 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎twist and untwist with minimal energy. 

00:00:50.154 --> 00:00:52.364 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎In addition, the tail 
‎of the seahorse is encased

00:00:52.364 --> 00:00:56.452 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎in overlapping bony plates
‎with many joints.

00:00:56.452 --> 00:00:59.622 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎When subjected 
‎to a potentially harmful force,

00:00:59.622 --> 00:01:01.707 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎the plates slide over one another,

00:01:01.707 --> 00:01:04.001 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎absorbing the energy.

00:01:04.001 --> 00:01:07.421 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎This can prevent damage 
‎to the seahorse’s spinal column.

00:01:08.130 --> 00:01:12.551 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎The design of the seahorse’s tail
‎could be applied to search-and-rescue robots,

00:01:12.551 --> 00:01:16.096 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎which need to be strong
‎and capable of bending and twisting

00:01:16.096 --> 00:01:17.973 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎in tight spaces.

00:01:17.973 --> 00:01:20.351 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎The same properties could be useful

00:01:20.351 --> 00:01:22.978 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎in some surgical equipment.

00:01:22.978 --> 00:01:25.230 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎According to Professor Ross Hatton:

00:01:25.230 --> 00:01:27.149 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎“Human engineers tend to build things

00:01:27.149 --> 00:01:30.110 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎“that are stiff 
‎so they can be controlled easily.

00:01:30.110 --> 00:01:33.614 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎“But nature makes things 
‎just strong enough not to break,

00:01:33.614 --> 00:01:37.076 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎“and then flexible enough 
‎to do a wide range of tasks.

00:01:37.076 --> 00:01:39.411 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎“That’s why we can learn 
‎a lot from animals

00:01:39.411 --> 00:01:42.581 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎that will inspire 
‎the next generations of robotics.”

00:01:42.581 --> 00:01:45.125 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎What do you think?

00:01:45.125 --> 00:01:47.836 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎Did the seahorse’s tail evolve?

00:01:47.836 --> 00:01:52.841 line:90%,end position:50%,center align:center
‎Or was it designed?

